  "prompt": "Can you be allergic to meat and fish?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to be allergic to meat and fish, although these types of allergies are relatively uncommon compared to other food allergies like those to peanuts, tree nuts, milk, eggs, and shellfish. \n\nAn allergy to meat can be triggered by specific proteins found in various types of meat, such as beef, pork, chicken, or lamb. One particular meat allergy is known as alpha-gal syndrome, which is caused by a reaction to the alpha-gal molecule found in red meat (beef, pork, lamb). This allergy is often triggered by a bite from the Lone Star tick, which introduces the alpha-gal molecule into the bloodstream.\n\nFish allergies typically involve an immune response to proteins found in fish, such as parvalbumin. People who are allergic to fish may react to various types of fish, including salmon, tuna, and cod. Symptoms of fish allergies can include hives, swelling, gastrointestinal issues, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.\n\nIf you suspect you have a meat or fish allergy, it is important to consult with a healthcare provider or an allergist for proper diagnosis and management. They can conduct tests and provide guidance on how to avoid allergens and manage symptoms.",
